betterquesting:10.desc:8: Does what is sounds like. It's an implosion compressor that doesn't use explosives. Although you can build it at UV, it requires UHV power to run.

Were you feeling slow? Tired of jumping for 1 block spaces? Perhaps not bulky enough?

The Dark Steel armor and tools are now available. Be sure to check the upgrades, they are craftables and do not require xp investment.

Some recipes use Molds, a non consumed item to help shape materials into different forms.

There are plate molds, ingot molds, gear molds, and even ball molds, the last of which you'll be needing in a few moments.

The chanced boost multiplied by the base chanced output chance of the recipe is the base chance in the large machine. The boost multiplied by the chance per tier of the recipe is the chance per tier in the large machine.

No Description

Noice. Most people don't even get to experience the HV age.

In this age you will unlock a lot of QoL and automation options, including AE2 autocrafting. But you may also decide to start mass automating at EV, things will get cheaper.
This machine turns dusts into gems, and has some other uses as well.

Congratulations, you have reached the first tier of progression: Steam! Steam machines are slow, need pipe connection, don't handle auto-output. But one must start somewhere.

Steam machines (not boilers!) have an exhaust vent, represented by a gray square on their backside by default. This vent can be moved using a wrench, but must remain unblocked. After every recipe, steam particles will be exhausted and §4damage entities standing by the vent§0§4§f§r. Keep the exhaust vent unblocked, or the machine will stop operating.


Steam age is sped up in this modpack as opposed to standard GregTech. Less grind, more joy!

Reminder: Wrenches are the best tool to break GT machines!
HV tier materials and components.
Welcome to <Placeholder: Gregicality Community Modpack>

One of the main components of the primitive processor is Red Alloy. It is an alloy of Redstone and Copper, and can be made in your Steam Alloy Smelter.

The rest of the items in the quest will guide you through making wires and then cables. Wires are rather expensive right now, but will get cheaper in the LV age.
betterquesting:10.name:8: Redstone Alloy, is it even Stone?

betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Just Enough Items will be your best friend in this journey. Learning how to use it will be crucial to help you out understand the ins and outs of the modpack.

Bookmark items regularly (default key 'A') so you don't have to remember what you needed to craft, and won't have to type the names over and over.

Most of the items have multiple recipes! Don't stop at the first apparent recipe and think it's unobtainable. Sometimes a material is only available from tiny dusts, sometimes it's available from fluids. It takes some practice.

You might realize that your inventory will quickly be filled up with junk, cobblestone, ores, everything. How can you fix this? A Satchel of course! In this modpack instead of normal Thermal ones, there are tiered satchels, from normal leather, into emerald.


§7§8First Satchel §f(Tier 1): 9 Slots

§8§7Iron satchel §f(Tier 2): 18 Slots

§eGold satchel §f(Tier 3): 27 Slots

§3§9Diamond satchel §f(Tier 4): 36 Slots

§aEmerald satchel §f(Tier 5): 45 Slots


Along with the original size, you are able to enchant satchels with the Holding enchants, with every Holding level 9 Slots are added.

Benzene, a gas that is considered an excellent power option by many players from MV to HV throughout many different versions of GregTech.

It also can be used in chemical processes starting in HV.

Many recipes will display it is obtained from distilling oil products. But it also is obtainable from Wood Tar.

This machine uses Hyper Fuel to produce EVEN MORE power than the Large Naquadah Reactor. If helium plasma is used in addition to hyper fuel, it will consume 2x the fuel with the same duration, but the power output is multiplied by 3.

Hot ingots are hot! They burn! How convenient it would be if something was automatically transferring them to your freshly made Vacuum Freezer. Well, we have that for you.

The Ore Dictionary filter lets you type an oredict and add a wildcard to automatically filter all the predicates. No need to specify items.

Here's a list of some the useful oredicts:

§5ingotHot*§r for hot ingots to send to your Vacuum Freezer

§5dustRegular*§r for plain clean dusts, it can help with ore processing

§5depletedFuel*§r for nuclear depleted fuels (not helpful right now, but will come handy)
Used in the Hyper Reactor I.

Smelting down 128 kanthal ingots took an eternity!! And now you have 2 sets of coils... So why not make a second EBF?? What a deal! As you progress further, you will want to make more and more EBFs.


In Gregicality, they are also used for alternate ore processing.

Epoxy will be your next polymer for circuit boards. All future boards will also require Epoxy as a base.

Making it will be the hardest challenge yet in terms of chemistry complexity. Similarly to Polyethylene, you have 2 main routes, including oil or excluding it. We will guide you through both, but this will be the last time. If you hate submitting fluids, rejoice!

Note that we purposely ignore the Naphtha recipe as it is very lossy and not intended for mass production.
Stellar Containment Casings are used in the Stellar Forge.

To power steam machines, you need steam of course!

There are different ways to produce steam, there is the Lava Boiler, the Solar Boiler, and the Large Boilers.

Boilers take some time to heat up, and once hot enough they will consume water and automatically output steam into connected pipes/machines. Be careful though, boilers can §4explode§0§r. The conditions for this to happen are as follows:
- The boiler is hot
- The boiler does not have any water inside
- You add water
Feeding boilers water before heating them up, and keep them permanently filled is perfectly safe. Their water consumption rate is also pretty slow, so you don't have to worry much about that.


The preferred way to produce steam will be High Pressure Boiler. In this modpack we give the option to skip regular boilers to speed up the steam age. Make 4 or even 8 HP Coal Boilers. That will be more than enough for the steam age, and enough for most of the LV age.

The EBF requires no less than 120eu/t to operate. You will need to supply 4Amps of LV to reach that power.

This is done either by either having 2 LV Energy hatches, or the Gregicality exclusive 4Amps LV energy hatch.

Get §eeither§r of those.

Large Turbines are multiblocks generating a lot of power. They function based on inertia, which means you need to feed them constantly in order for them to reach max output, else they are worthless.

Fuel consumption is 256x bigger than what JEI indicates for LV recipes, or 4x the amount of a HV turbine, regardless of turbine efficiency.
Base power output is 8192eu/t (one IV amp) at 100% efficiency.
Energy efficiency is 4 times as high, assuming 100% efficency.

Rotor Holder comes in three tiers, HV is for max 6000RPM which is default. LuV and MAX rotor holders increase the RPM limit for some more efficiency.

However, the main efficiency comes from the rotor itself. There are 4 tiers of rotor:
Small - Available with Titanium at late HV
Medium - Available with Tungstensteel at late EV
Large - Available with Osmium at IV
Huge - Available with Rutherfordium after fusion in LuV

Materials used in rotors provide different efficiency values. You can only start with poor rotors, which sadly means the huge efficiency boost from turbines will be mostly negated.

If you hate oil, glycerol is your only option.

This option requires a lot of seed or fish oil to be useful. Although it gives Bio Diesel, which can be used along with the rest of your power setup.

Tools using energy to save a lot of durability. Usually one electric tool can last an entire playthrough before it breaks.

The mining drill doubles up as a pickaxe and a shovel. It also has a ridiculous mining speed, it can replace your wrench to mine machines, wires, and such.

The Coke Oven is a staple of the early game in many modpacks.

Use it for Charcoal and Coal Coke. It's modified to be pretty fast in here!

You will probably want multiple Coke Ovens. To make it easier on you, here's a tip: they can share walls.


For automation purposes, the main block does not accept automatic input and output. The Hatch is used to perform such things.
The Hatch can be placed on any centered side (this includes top and bottom).
The Hatch is not limited to one (you can replace more bricks with more hatches).
The Hatch automatically outputs creosote to a connected tank.
The Hatch can be used to automatically insert and extract items. Place a hopper feeding into it for insertion, and a hopper below a centered hatch for extraction.
We are gonna need some §cexplos§rives to generation some §cimplos§rions inside our Implosion Compressor.

"Excuse me Mr. Questbook Writer, why do you include a MV machine in my LV questline!??"

If we were to include a LV Thermal Centrifuge, the best you would be able to do with it would be to use it as a decoration block! The Thermal Centrifuge requires 60eu/t to operate, which means a LV machine cannot process any ore!

This machine is so bad that Gregicality has a config setting to double its output.

With the config off, you're better off centrifuging purified dusts in a regular Centrifuge.

I'll give you a disassembler for your valiant effort to complete this quest. You know what to do.

Propene is a hydrocarbon, obtained only from oil processing. It can also be used to make Isoprene to synthesize Rubber.

While it is not strictly required, having oil set up will help you smoothly transition to higher tiers. §lEspecially§r with the Distillation Tower.

Explaining the whole ore processing system is out of the scope of this introduction, so we will keep it simple for now. More details in LV.

Macerating is still an ore doubler like in other mods. But there is a twist, it does not give dusts directly! Crushed Ores are meant for more advanced ore processing. One Crushed Ore will convert to one dust.


To get the an Impure Dust, hammer the Crushed Ore. This is done either by using a Hammer tool in the crafting table, or using the Steam Forge Hammer.

The Impure Dust can be smelted in the Furnace to get the Ingot, however mixed ores (Limonite, Chalcopyrite) will only give nuggets over ingots.

The Impure Dust can also be thrown in a vanilla Cauldron filled with water to clean it and turn it into a regular dust. Throw them in full stacks to consume less water per single dust.


§lNote: Macerating, hammering, and then smelting (sometimes into nuggets) is really time consuming in the steam age! Resource efficiency can be ignored for now. Nobody will blame you for smelting ores directly into ingots.

Did we tell you how much we wanted to help you in the early game? Perhaps we forgot... So more help!

Use your Bronze Coins to get more resources. Really, spend them!!

Black Bronze... Black Steel... Rose Gold... Why not Blue Steel and Red steel while we're at it? Ah, all of them exist.

While not that useful, these alloys will be required in the future.

This quest features Black Steel, which you will need for Applied Energistics.

If you hate having your Steel GT tools break over and over, make some Blue Steel or Vanadium Steel. They have higher durability.
Now wouldn't it be nice if you could have infinite automated water for your boilers? We got you covered!

Get Plant Balls from compressing excess saplings from your tree farm. If this is not enough, top it up with carrots or some other crop.

Due to Integrated Circuit configuration, you may need a dedicated Pyrolyse Oven for this step.
Early on, you can get away with making a lot of Fermented Biomass in bulk, then switching your Oven for charcoal.

Feeling creative? Want a tool to help you better with multiblocks?

We got you covered! The Freedom Wrench is a great tool with modes that you can cycle with shift right clicking air.

Projection, Pespective, Debug modes help visualize the structure of a multiblock similarly to how MBTweaker.

Building mode is a big time saver! Right click on a multiblock controller and it will automatically place the blocks from your inventory. It will try to reproduce the structure shown by JEI, so you might still have to places hatches yourself, but the wrench still did 90% of the job.


We're not done, shift right click on a controller will rotate it, under any axes. Sideways Electric Blast Furnace, upside down Distillation Tower, you choose! It's a freedom wrench after all.

Diesel is probably the most classic Steam alternative there is in GregTech. It is obtained by mixing Light Fuel and Heavy Fuel.

Using regular Oil, a setup should go as follows:
- 3 Distilleries for (Sulfuric) Light Fuel
- 2 Distilleries for (Sulfuric) Heavy Fuel.

Heavy Oil is an even better Heavy Fuel source, as the ratio is much greater.


Such a setup can easily power a base for the MV and HV age. But be careful as running out of Oil can be problematic!
GregTech Food Option (GTFO) is an addon to Gregicality that adds several chains to acqiure food items.

Both the Central Monitor and the Freedom Wrench are an addition from KilaBash.

The Central Monitor is a modular multiblock to display information, images, and remotely access machines from its screens. Going into the details about how it works is rather complicated, so we will just say it can do a lot of cool stuff. Check it out sooner than later!

Of course, you've probably noticed that you can't make Bread as usual, and you can only acquire it through the §6Baking Oven§6§r. This particular multiblock allows you to "bake" food items manually, much like a Primitive Blast Furnace can. It also requires fuel to run recipes, the amount of which is represented in JEI by a few common fuel items.

This also allows you to acquire other interesting food items, such as pizza and pastries.

The amount of adobe bricks required for this multiblock is not particularly easy to acquire, but collecting some wheat should ease things up a bit. Kaolinite and Bentonite are especially useful for the construction of this.

If you've been using the Baking Oven, you may have become slightly annoyed at the lack of options it has for automation.
However, the §6Electric Baking Oven§r should resolve that issue for you!

This particular multiblock is a little unconventional in how it consumes energy. Rather than consuming energy based on the recipe it's running, it consumes energy based on its §ctemperature§r, which you can set in the GUI. This consumption increases exponentially as the temperature increases.

Note that the temperature will not immediately be set to whatever you like, as it has to heat up or cool itself down first, at 5 Kelvin a second.

Also, that energy usage does gate automation of a few items to a rather late period, such as pizza, which can only be made in this machine at HV.

Congrats! You are now ready to make Bread (or Baguettes, if you prefer).

However, you will need some Salt (and preferably Soda Ash, aka Baking Soda) to get started, so make sure you have a Salt vein.

Then, just make some Dough, a Wooden Form of your choice, and get a Rolling Pin to get some Unbaked Bread.

Finally, just roast it in your Baking Oven.

Slices things up. You only really need LV Slicing Machines for everyday purposes.

However, you do need Stainless Steel for the Slicing Blades, which does gate the usage of this to late MV.

These are pretty nice for getting into some early-game Biology chains.
Most importantly, these move back the gate for several GTFO food items back to HV.
The Electromagnetic Separator can get some additional outputs from some ores. Not too important.
<PLACEHOLDER>

Converting MV into LV voltage or vice versa requires a transformer. The default transformer with default configuration takes 1 MV Amp in its input side, and outputs 4 LV Amps on the opposite side (be sure to use 4x cables!). Transforming up is possible but generally less desirable.

Making an electric network and transforming down for LV machines is not recommended in MV, cable loss is still too high. Using single block generators locally is preferred.

Creosote Oil will have its uses, but for now it is worthless and it could easily clog up your Coke Oven.

Extra Utilities isn't in this modpack, but you still have the Universal Bin from NuclearCraft.

If you can't afford this right now and your Coke Oven ends up filled with Creosote, break and replace the block.

Shaping bricks by hand is a little bit of a tricky task! Some kind of mold would help.

Next step is the Coke Oven, you're going to need 116 Coke Oven Bricks, which needs 75 sand and 45 clay.
Gather a lot more clay, it is an essential early game material.

The early game usually tends to be pretty slow in GregTech. Some modpacks embrace it, some of them skip steps to make it less tedious.

As the goal of the modpack is to provide a full GregTech + Gregicality experience, all the mechanics are kept. However, we will make it easier on you, with easier recipes and quest rewards. The help will be greater in the early game, and will gradually go away as you progress further. You can also decide to ignore rewards if you wish to be a purist.

Notable modifications for this modpack:
- Circuit recipes give twice as many circuits
- Steam age related recipes are cheaper
- Steel in the Primitive Blast Furnace is faster
- Mob loot is not required (hostile mobs are disabled anyways)


As finding an iron vein may take a little bit of time and mining, we will give you a fair deal. Delay mining for later and collect some basic materials instead. Settle down somewhere and we will give you some iron to start off with tools. You may be able to progress up to LV age solely on Quest rewards.

These are the other GregTech tools needed before you reach LV age.

§lMortar:§r
A crafting tool to grind down some materials.

§lScrewdriver:§r
Another crafting tool. Useful as a configuration tool for covers and multiblock controllers, will be useful later.

§lWire Cutter:§r
Used for the inefficient crafting recipe for wires before you get to the LV age. Can also mine wires, but the wrench does the same job in GTCE.

§lSoft Hammer:§r
A tool to enable/disable when you right click on them. Very useful to save on energy and on steam.

Note: Any material type for these tools will work towards the completion of the quest.

Grind down Copper and Tin using a mortar, combine the dusts in the crafting table, smelt the output and you've got yourself some Bronze.

4 Bronze Ingots won't get you far, although a stack will last a decent while. Batch crafting, both now and later, will be a lifesaver.

Completing this quest unlocks the Steam Age.
Better Furnaces might help you with smelting down many ores. They're not as important as in Omnifactory, due to Gregicality having a fancy Steam Oven multiblock available during the steam age.
An introduction to the Purple Drink chain.

GregTech has variants of the vanilla tools. They are not necessarily worth getting, with the exception of the Axe.

The Axe from GregTech chops down trees instantly! Who needs OreExcavation?

Axes made out metal require tools to be crafted, but the flint Axe is craftable the vanilla way.

These hammers are excellent for mining, they break blocks in a 3x3 area.

Iron hammers require GregTech tools to craft.

Diamond hammers require the Forge Hammer available in Steam Age.

Ore Generation is heavily revamped. All vanilla ores are removed in favor of rarer, massive veins containing a few ore types.

When exploring in the world, you'll find traces of ores on the surface, they indicate a specific vein is below them. You can check JEI to see what type of ore veins exist.


Iron, Copper and other common metals do not come only from ores with the same names. Many ores convert directly into the main metal they are made of. Refer to the Ore Tab to get a listing of the ores.

Even though it's not required right now, you'll be facing off a time gate before the LV age if you don't get ready beforehand. This is due to resistors requiring both paper and resin, and also insulated cables taking both black carpets and strings.

Any seasoned minecraft player would setup a medium sized sugar canes and wheat farm, but let's make sure you do not skip that step!

Once this is done, also setup a Sheep ranch and dye them black. Collect the black wool regularly.


This manual farming won't be needed for long, since by the time you're settled in the LV age, you won't need it anymore.

Most metals needed MV voltage to be melted down using a Fluid Extractor. You can now setup both Fluid Extractor and Fluid Solidifier to shape metals into anything, similarly to the extruder. Alternatively you can use it to recover metal if you crafted it in useless shapes.

You can now make rotors at a 4:1 ratio.

Did you run out of space when automating? Would you wish machines had a additional sides, or rather §bfaces§r?

The Phantomfaces act as an extra access point to the block they are linked to, wirelessly.

You can use them to:
- Avoid having pipes go in all the directions (not too important, EIO conduits help with that already)
- Automate machines, such as the chemical reactor, which need a lot of different inputs and outputs while keeping them organised
- Connect more ME Interfaces to a single machine / input bus so it can handle a lot more than 9 patterns.

Read the Actually Additions book for more details.

If you hate GTCE fluid pipes (like most of us do), you can get EnderIO Pressurized Fluid Conduits.

You can insert/extract fluids in and out of machines by clicking on the corresponding tanks with a fluid container (a bucket will do).

There are two recipes for Concrete. One of them requires an unconsumed Integration Circuit, which is not obtainable right away.

By now this is the machine you probably crafted the most as the LV variant. It does not stop there, you will need the HV chemical reactor for various processes.

Despite being more expensive, you might want to consider building full chains with HV chemical reactors when only one recipe requires HV, that way you won't have to transform up or down. Reduce the overclocking on some of your machines to keep a safe energy consumption.

The HV chemical reactor now allows you to get Ammonia directly in one step, from nitrogen and hydrogen. That's of couse only one of many recipes.

Congratulations, you've made some Steel, the main LV material and used extensively throughout the entire modpack.

From now on, keep mass producing Steel, you will need lots of it!

Let's hope your Sheep ranch is going well, cable insulation does indeed require black carpet and string.
However, string can only be obtained in large quantities from macerating wool.

The IPBF is a variable size PBF which also enables automation.

The main block - the controller - will only display information and does not take items.
Instead, items are inserted into Input Bus(es), you may have Input Buses on either side of the IPBF. For better automation, use one for iron, and one for charcoal.
Steel and Dark Ashes are produced in the Output Bus, at the opposite side of the controller.

Buses auto insert and extract to/from connected inventories on the dot side.

Note: It is better to wait until the beginning of LV Age to make this, due to Bus recipes requiring a LV machine hull and cables.
Sticky Resin is obtained from cutting down Rubber Trees, that's why we made included them in an earlier quest!

Paper is a little bit trickier to obtain and the ratio sugar canes -> paper is considerably worse. You've got that sugar cane farm going don't you?

In LV age, you will be able to obtain paper much more efficiently, simply from wood if you wish.

Bronze Pipes will be the first way you can transfer steam around, they are also used in crafting recipes.
Be careful to not hug them if they have steam inside, you will feel the heat.

GTCE fluid pipes are mediocre, consider switching over to EnderIO fluid conduits as soon as possible.

GregTech has a lot of tools! There are variants of tools from vanilla and other mods, mining tools, crafting tools, and even electric tools.

§lHammer:§r
Your main crafting tool. Used to craft plates from two ingots, for tools, for some modified recipes (such as the bucket), and to crush things in general.
Mining Ores with the hammer gives crushed ores at a rate greater than 1, but we will give an introduction to ore processing in another quest.

Craft your first hammer using 6 iron ingots and a stick.


You may notice many recipes are listed for these tools. It's because they all share the same ID. In JEI it may show them either as Aluminium or Darmstadtium. But do worry not, even iron will work!
Hit this when updating the modpack to reload to the new quest database.

There are several different kinds of chips, most of which give different effects.

If you're looking for the easiest of these to do, I highly recommend giving Syals a taste. Don't mind its tooltip ;)

This custom machine made for this modpack will let you exchange your LV coins for valuable ores.
Spend your coins!

Coin rewards will become less and less important, and will eventually phase out. But that's where the miners will kick in!

Nitric Acid, used in a lot of chemical reactions, to dissolve metals or even make explosives (do not attempt at home).

You can make it from Nitrogen Dioxide for now.

You will need a couple buckets of this to setup the gold processing. You may use this for Industrial TNT in HV. And with EV you'll start using it extensively.
Who wants French Fries?

Hydrochloric Acid is used a lot in chemical reactions.

Most reactions requiring Chlorine gas will give off Hydrochloric Acid as a byproduct. You can decide to electrolyze it to recover Chlorine.

You also need this for gold processing. It is a good idea to passively produce this sooner than later.

EV age! What normally is the beginning of late game in GTCE, is more like the beginning of the early game in here! Long journey awaits.

Congratulations on reaching this point. EV marks the beginning of diving into the awesomeness of Gregicality.


There a lot of recipe chains in this age. Let me list some of them:
- PTFE, a polymer, this was technically doable at HV
- Platinum chain, the so called "platline", for Platinum and Palladium primarily
- Tungsten chain, the gate to IV
- Rare Earth chain, also called REE (Rare Earth Elements)
- Pitchblende chain, but that one is preferable to do at IV


EV also a good age to start tackling on all the optional advanced ore processing:
- Vanadium
- Sapphire and Ruby Slurry
- Bauxite
- Lepidolite
I hope you've been farming a lot of lemons and limes.

The Platinum Processing "Platline" follows real-life chemistry thoroughly, the same reactions are used in order to extract various metals.

The Platline provides:
- Platinum
- Palladium
- Iridium
- Osmium
- Rhodium
- Ruthenium
- Rhenium

In EV, you will only need Platinum and Palladium. If you decide to expand the chain during the EV age to other ores (except Rhenium which is UV tier), check the quests in Chemistry Tab.

The recycling aspect of the Palladium Chain is easier to deal with

The Palladium Salt is sifted directly into Metallic Powder.
Tungstensteel, the main IV material.

Barite cannot be electrolyzed directly into Barium and Oxygen. It requires a unique chemical process.

While none of the steps are particularly complicated, they would need dedicated machines which makes automating the processing in HV age undesired. You may only need 9 barium dust to progress to IV, but making a full stack will grant you extra safety.

When automating the processing line, make sure so most (or every) Barium compound is requestable, as they have their use in other chains.

Rare Earth Element (REE) processing is used to obtain a lot of materials.

Not every product is equally useful, but this will be your first source of Yttrium, and a better source of Neodymium.

Before diving in, you're gonna need that complicated solution. It's a catalyst and won't be consumed in recipes, so make it just once.

The steps of the REE processing.

It is heavily recommended to use a highly overclocked Large Centrifuge for everything giving chanced output due to the huge bonus.

To recover all the metals from the oxide variants, automate an EBF with 1 input bus permanently filled with Carbon.
Yttrium is used in many alloys starting with IV age.
The base of all circuits is the Circuit Board! These Boards require preparation to be used, and this one uses 8 copper wires.

The Forge Hammer is an extremely helpful early game machine.

It can perform most of the recipes that normally are done in the crafting table with a Hammer (Hammer + item).
It can make plates more efficiently, at a 3:2 ratio.

Wrought Iron was the most common form of malleable iron before widespread and efficient steel production came around.

Wrought Iron can be used for tools, and has 1.5x the base durability compared to iron.
Smelt Iron Ingots in a furnace to make hot Iron, and hammer it in a crafting table. No mittens needed, as Steve is fairly heat-proof.

Don't turn all of your iron into wrought iron! You cannot convert it back, and they are both used.
Resistors reduce the voltage across them in an electric circuit.

Congratulations! You've completed your first step out of Steam Age. Soon you will be making electric machines.

Circuits will become significantly easier to make as you progress throughout LV.

Now, just make an LV Machine Hull and a few LV Electric Motors, and you can start the LV Age!

The Steam Mixer is a steam machine that mixes items and/or fluids into others.

Recipes in JEI display eu/t which refers to electric machines. Steam machines can perform these recipes up to 32eu/t.
This machine can compress various materials. It can turn ingots into blocks, as well as some materials into plates.

Two ores contain Tunsgten. Tungstate and Scheelite.

The process for both ores is nearly the same, but one requires an extra input. Automate the one you find more convenient now, and the other one later.

You can complete the quest with §eeither§r task completed.

The Steam Grinder is the multiblock version of the steam macerator.

It utilizes more steam to macerate 8 items at once per recipe. This machine has utility up to HV age, or even beyond.
Similar to the regular Macerator, only the first item will be produced from recipes shown in JEI.

Considering the cost of this multiblock, you may want to put it off until the LV age, once it gets a little easier to make.
EV Components are as follows.

The Macerator, so well known as the essential machine for ore doubling, is no different in here! However... Ore processing can get in the way, we will take a little bit of time explaining how it goes in the simple details in the following quest.

When consulting JEI, you may notice that many Macerator recipes output 3 items. However this Macerator will only output the first item in the list! The same will apply to other macerators up to HV.


The Macerator also unlocks the Steam Grinder, which is significantly better.

Steam Multiblock Furnace! This machine smelts 8 items at a time.

A really efficient way to smelt a lot of materials, will last a while even after you progress into electric ages.
Consult JEI to form the multiblock.

This particular multiblock may be a little difficult to construct at the steam tier, but it should be a piece of cake by LV.
You can also get it from Dungeon chests, but that's no fun.

Your main component in MV age.

The cheaper recipe is available only after you get the MV assembler.
<PLACEHOLDER>

Many questions arise regarding the EBF, and GregTech multiblocks in general.
The most common is: "Why is my EBF not working?".

First, make sure the multiblock is assembled correctly. You can shift right click the controller with an empty hand. If a block appears red, it means you placed something that should not be there. If the controller itself is red, it means you are not meeting the requirement for hatches/buses or minimum casings. Check the JEI preview to figure out what you need. Not all machines are hollow.

Multiblocks hate chunk borders, this can result in causing them to load incorrectly. Always keep the entire structure of a multiblock in a single chunk.

Any tier of bus/hatches will work to assemble most multiblocks. But you always need to make sure it has space to output the items, or it will simply not operate. If the EBF has a fluid recipe, be sure to add Fluid Hatches.

Overclocking happens when the EU/t cost of a recipe is within a lower voltage tier than the machine handling it. The machine will consume four times as much power, and process the recipe faster. There is a catch though, you lose energy efficiency.

Remember the case with the LV Wiremill? Wire recipe costs were 8eu/t, and are overclocked to 32eu/t.
With a MV Wiremill, the recipe would be overclocked once more, consuming 128eu/t to fit the current voltage tier.

The speed boost depends on the base cost of the recipe:
- 16EU/t and less: 2x speed boost (2x net energy usage per overclock)
- between 17EU/t and 32EU/t: 2.8x speed boost (1.42x net energy usage per overclock)

Don't ask me why this is so weird, GTCE is GTCE. A work is in progress to improve overclocking.

Every single LV machine requires this.

Electricity is transported using LV wires or cables. Use insulated cables over wires if you value your life.

Cables have energy loss, so it's best to stick machines as close to the power source as possible.

EU is the energy unit for electricity. EU/t (EU per tick) is the power unit, but also used to represent voltage.

LV - Low Voltage - goes up to 32 EU/t, which means LV machines are capable of doing recipes up to 32EU/t. Anything higher will be considered a higher voltage, and you will need MV or machines to perform them. Be sure to always check the voltage of recipes.
